        "# About Data\n",
        "\n",
        "## Row {height=\"100%\"}\n",
        "\n",
        "### Column {width=\"100%\"}\n",
        "\n",
        "## Row\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.column width=\"100%\"}\n",
        "\n",
        "### Introduction\n",
        "\n",
        "The aim of choosing these indicators is evaluating the **Impact of Government Health Expenditure on Global Maternal Mortality**. This project serves as the capstone for the GRAPH Course, demonstrating a comprehensive end-to-end data science workflow — from environment setup and raw data ingestion to graphics and GitHub deployment.\n",
        "\n",
        "**SDG Target 3.1** aims to reduce the global maternal mortality ratio to less than 70 per 100,000 live births by 2030. This dashboard explores: *How efficiently do different nations convert public health spending into the preservation of maternal lives?*\n",
        "\n",
        "### Key Observations\n",
        "\n",
        "- Health spending increases across most countries over time, especially after 2010\n",
        "- **USA** is the highest spender with rapid growth post-2012\n",
        "- **Nigeria** shows the most volatility — a sharp rise around 2004–2006, drop, then modest recovery by 2015\n",
        "- A clear gap exists between developed (USA, Germany) and developing countries (Kenya, Nigeria)\n",
        "- Lower government health spending is associated with higher maternal mortality ratios in many African countries\n",
        "\n",
        ":::"
      ],
      "id": "b21f447e"
